</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
Compiled by YEMI TOURE 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
On the Lam: More than 200 supporters, many wearing "Run Bambi Run" T-shirts, 
rallied Friday in Milwaukee to wish a convicted killer luck in evading capture. 
Lawrencia Bembenek, 31, a former model and policewoman convicted of murdering 
her then-husband's ex-wife in 1981, is believed to have fled with her fiance 
after scaling a fence July 15 at a Wisconsin women's prison. 
</P>
<P>
Supporters maintained that Bembenek received an unfair trial and was the victim 
of a police setup. 
</P>
<P>
Book Judgment: London judge Michael Wright on Friday temporarily banned author 
Malcolm Barker from publishing "Courting Disaster" anywhere in the world 
because it reportedly gives intimate details about Britain's royal family. The 
judge ordered a delay in enforcing the ban until today pending an appeal. The 
book is already on sale in Canada, the United States and Bermuda. Barker was a 
clerk in Buckingham Palace. 
</P>
<P>
Adjudged: A former Playboy model was sentenced late last week in Milwaukee to 
10 months in prison for evading taxes on $686,000 that an aging millionaire 
paid her during a five-year sexual relationship with both the model and her 
sister. Lynnette Harris, 35, was convicted in May by a federal jury that did 
not accept her claims that the money represented tax-free gifts. Harris 
received money from David Kritzik of suburban Shorewood, who died last summer 
at age 89. "I got involved in this relationship and it has turned out to be a 
nightmare," Harris said. 
</P>
<P>
Another Break-In?: A co-defendant in the drug-trafficking case of former 
Panamanian strongman Manuel Noriega was arrested at an exclusive home in Miami 
once owned by President Richard Nixon. Roberto Steiner was arrested Thursday at 
the mansion, law officials said Friday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
