<P>
AD-FREE MS. BACK ON NEWSSTANDS WITH FOCUS ON 'WORLD OF WOMEN' 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
NEW YORK 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Eight months after suspending publication, Ms. magazine went back to the 
newsstand today without advertising. 
</P>
<P>
The magazine also has a slightly new name, Ms.: The World of Women, which its 
backers say better reflects its worldwide scope. 
</P>
<P>
The first issue of the redesigned magazine is selling for $4.50 a copy. 
Subscriptions are $40 a year for six issues. 
</P>
<P>
The cover of the first issue shows a tiny globe nestled between two women's 
hands. "Collector's edition," it says across the top. "No advertising, 
editorially free. Ms. Lives." 
</P>
<P>
The 17-year-old Ms. suspended publication after the November, 1989, issue. Its 
new owner is Dale Lang, who also publishes Working Woman, Working Mother, Sassy 
and Success magazines. 
</P>
