<P>
THE SIDELINES; 
</P>
<P>
PITCHER RED BARRETT, 75, DIES 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Wire Services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
WILSON, N.C. 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Charles (Red) Barrett, who set the major league record for the fewest pitches 
in a nine-inning game, has died at his home after a long illness. He was 75. 
</P>
<P>
Barrett, while pitching for the Boston Braves, set the record for the fewest 
pitches in a nine-inning game in 1944 when he faced 27 batters and threw only 
58 pitches in a 2-0 victory over the Cincinnati Reds. 
</P>
<P>
He was voted the International League's most valuable player in 1942 and was 
named to the National League All-Star team in 1945. He pitched in the World 
Series for St. Louis in 1946 and for the Braves in 1948. 
</P>
<P>
Barrett, who died Saturday, also pitched for Cincinnati and compiled a career 
record of 69-69 with an ERA of 3.53. 
</P>
</TEXT>
